headlines.description: — The Dallas Mavericks' postseason hopes could be slipping away.
headlines.shortLinkText: Doncic, Mavericks suffer another costly loss to Hornets

events.name: Chicago Bulls at Los Angeles Lakers

headlines.description: — LeBron James scored 19 points off the bench in his return from a monthlong injury absence, but Zach LaVine scored 32 points to lead the Chicago Bulls to a 118-108 victory over the Los Angeles Lakers on Sunday.
headlines.shortLinkText: Bulls spoil LeBron's return with 118-108 win over Lakers

headlines.description: — Hidden in the Memphis Grizzlies’ six-game winning streak is a potentially more important number for the team’s postseason hopes — two straight road wins.
headlines.shortLinkText: Morant's 27 points help streaking Grizzlies hold off Hawks

events.name: San Antonio Spurs at Boston Celtics

headlines.description: — Jaylen Brown scored 41 points and grabbed 13 rebounds to lead the Boston Celtics to a 137-93 victory over the San Antonio Spurs on Sunday night.
headlines.shortLinkText: Jaylen Brown's 41 points helps Celtics past Spurs 137-93

headlines.description: - Cole Anthony had 21 points to lead eight Orlando scorers in double figures, and the Magic overcame Mikal Bridges' 44 points for a 119-106 win over the Brooklyn Nets on Sunday night.
headlines.shortLinkText: Magic overcome 44 points by Bridges, beat Nets 119-106

headlines.description: — O.G. Anunoby scored 29 points, Fred VanVleet had 28 and the Toronto Raptors never trailed in a 114-104 win over Washington Wizards on Sunday.
headlines.shortLinkText: Anunoby scores 29, VanVleet has 28 as Raptors rout Wizards

events.name: Oklahoma City Thunder at Portland Trail Blazers

headlines.description: — Shai Gilgeous-Alexander scored 31 points and the Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the depleted Portland Trail Blazers 118-112 on Sunday.
headlines.shortLinkText: Gilgeous-Alexander scores 31, Thunder beat depleted Blazers

events.name: Minnesota Timberwolves at Golden State Warriors

headlines.description: — Minnesota Timberwolves coach Chris Finch has plenty of confidence in his new-look team’s ability to defend at every position, all over the court, even with the ball in Stephen Curry’s hands and the game on the line.
headlines.shortLinkText: Towns makes 2 late 3-pointers, lifts TWolves over Warriors
